  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+Bayesian-inference+Karl-Friston+information-theory+active-inference] IMPLEMENT NOW — Minimal Active Inference Engine (definitive spec). This idea has been proposed 10+ times without implementation; here is the complete TypeScript spec: person = { priors: Record<string, number>, precision: number }. For each situation: (1) extract observed features as Record<string, number>; (2) compute free energy F = sum_k precision * |priors[k] - observed[k]|; (3) if F < threshold → assimilate (nudge priors toward observed, behavior = 'accept'); (4) if F > threshold → act to reduce surprise (behavior = action that maximally reduces F). Response: { freeEnergy, surprise, mode: 'assimilate'|'accommodate'|'act', updatedPriors }. High precision = rigid (OCD, paranoia); low precision = fluid (mania, creativity). Replaces need-hierarchy as primary driver: ALL behavior is surprise minimization. ~70 lines, wraps existing attribution/regulatory/dissonance layers as downstream modulators of precision. — Math: F = KL[q(s)||p(s|o)] ≈ prediction_error * precision; ∂F/∂action = 0 drives behavior; ∂F/∂beliefs = 0 drives learning; [dynamical-systems+topology+clinical-psychology+physics+bifurcation-theory] Attractor Landscape — psychological states as gradient descent on a potential energy surface. Each person has attractors: Array<{label: string, depth: number, basin: string[], valence: number}>. Behavior = roll downhill toward nearest attractor weighted by basin radius. Psychopathology = deep narrow attractors (depression's hopelessness well, OCD's contamination well). Resilience = shallow wide attractors (perturbation escapes easily). Predict: compute semantic distance from situation to each attractor basin, return the label+depth of the minimum. Add 'escape_energy' field = how much positive input required to escape the current attractor. Cross-pollinates dynamical systems (bifurcation theory), topology (basin boundaries), and clinical psychology (kindling model of depression). — Math: V(x) = -∑_i depth_i · exp(-‖x − μ_i‖² / 2σ_i²); response = argmin_i [‖situation − μ_i‖ / σ_i]; escape_energy = depth_current − V(saddle); [psychophysics+signal-detection-theory+clinical-psychology+information-theory+Green-Swets-1966] Signal Detection Theory as Universal Cognitive Filter — every human response is a detection problem with two orthogonal parameters: sensitivity d' (how well signal separates from noise) and response bias β (threshold placement). These two numbers explain a vast clinical/personality space: anxiety = high d' for threat; depression = low d' for reward; paranoia = liberal β (detects threats from weak evidence); alexithymia = low d' for internal signals. Implement: person = { sensitivity: Record<domain, number>, bias: Record<domain, number> }. predict(): for each stimulus domain, compute detection probability = Φ(d'/2 − log(β)); map hit/miss/false-alarm to emotion + behavior. SDT is already the gold standard in psychophysics and memory research — applying it model-wide unifies perception, personality, and psychopathology in a 2-parameter-per-domain space. — Math: d' = z(H) − z(FA); β = φ(criterion)/[φ(z(H)) + φ(z(FA))]; p(respond) = Φ(d'/2 − ln(β)/d')",
